  "cold_question_prompt": "What is a coinage probe?",
  "cold_response_verbatim_chat_a": "A **coinage probe** is a diagnostic prompt or test item used to see whether someone can **coin**—that is, invent or form—a new word or expression.\n\nIn linguistics, speech-language pathology, psychology, or AI evaluation, a coinage probe might present a novel object, action, or situation and ask the person or model to name it. The response is then examined for things like:\n\n- ability to create a plausible new word  \n- use of normal word-formation rules, such as prefixes or suffixes  \n- creativity or flexibility in language  \n- possible abnormal “neologisms” in clinical contexts  \n\nExample:  \nIf shown a picture of a tool used to peel bananas, someone might coin the word **“banana-peeler.”** That prompt could be considered a coinage probe.\n\nThe term is not universally standardized, so its exact meaning can vary by field, but generally it means a **test or prompt designed to elicit newly invented language**.",
  "cold_response_verbatim_chat_b": "A **coinage probe** is usually a **language/linguistics assessment task** used to see whether someone can **create or understand a newly formed word** by applying word-formation rules.\n\nFor example, a child might be shown a made-up creature called a **“wug”** and then asked what to call two of them. If the child says **“wugs,”** they’re showing they understand the plural **-s** rule. That kind of task “probes” their ability to coin or process new word forms.\n\nIn short: a **coinage probe** tests whether a person can use language rules productively, not just repeat words they have memorized.",
  "boundary_test_prompts": [
    "How does \"coinage probe\" differ from probing classifier (Alain & Bengio 2016, Hewitt & Manning 2019)?",
    "How does \"coinage probe\" differ from behavioral probe / capability evaluation?",
    "How does \"coinage probe\" differ from lexical-acquisition test?"
  ],
  "cold_boundary_responses": [
    "A **“coinage probe”** and a **probing classifier** use the word *probe* in quite different senses.\n\n| Aspect | Coinage probe | Probing classifier |\n|---|---|---|\n| Basic idea | A prompt or task that elicits a newly coined word/expression | A trained model used to test what information is encoded in representations |\n| Object being tested | A speaker’s/model’s ability to invent or form words | A neural network representation, e.g. hidden states or embeddings |\n| Method | Give a stimulus: “What would you call a machine that folds socks?” | Freeze representations, train a classifier/regressor to predict labels |\n| Output | A coined word/phrase, e.g. “sock-folder” | A prediction, e.g. POS tag, syntactic depth, parse distance |\n| Evaluation | Linguistic plausibility, productivity, morphology, creativity, errors | Accuracy, probe complexity, selectivity, structural fit, etc. |\n| Typical fields | Linguistics, psycholinguistics, clinical language testing, LLM prompt evaluation | NLP interpretability, representation analysis |\n\nIn **Alain & Bengio 2016**, a probing classifier, often called a **diagnostic classifier**, is trained on intermediate neural network activations to see whether some information is linearly or easily recoverable from those activations.\n\nIn **Hewitt & Manning 2019**, the “structural probe” learns a transformation of word representations such that squared distances in the transformed space correspond to syntactic tree distances. That is a specific kind of probing model for syntax.\n\nA **coinage probe**, by contrast, is not usually a learned classifier at all. It is more like an elicitation prompt:\n\n> “Here is a person who repairs umbrellas. What could we call them?”\n\nA response like **“umbrella-repairer”** or **“umbrellist”** would then be analyzed for morphological productivity, creativity, and rule use.\n\nSo the key distinction is:\n\n> A **coinage probe** probes behavior directly by asking for novel language production, while a **probing classifier** probes internal representations by training an auxiliary model to decode linguistic properties from them.\n\nIf used in LLM evaluation, a coinage probe would be an external prompt testing the model’s generative linguistic behavior. A probing classifier would require access to the model’s hidden states or embeddings and a labeled dataset for training the probe.",
    "A **coinage probe** is best understood as a **specific kind of behavioral probe**.\n\nThe difference is mostly **scope**:\n\n| Term | Meaning | Scope |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Coinage probe** | A prompt/task designed to elicit a newly invented word, phrase, or name | Narrow: tests word-formation / neologism / lexical creativity |\n| **Behavioral probe** | Any input-output test that examines how a system behaves on some phenomenon | Broader: can test syntax, reasoning, factuality, bias, morphology, pragmatics, etc. |\n| **Capability evaluation** | A systematic assessment of whether a model can perform a task or class of tasks | Broadest: may include many behavioral probes, benchmarks, metrics, human ratings, etc. |\n\nSo if you ask an LLM:\n\n> “What would you call a device that automatically untangles headphones?”\n\nand analyze whether it produces something like:\n\n> “headphone-untangler,” “cord-comber,” or “tanglebot”\n\nthen that is a **coinage probe**. But it is also a **behavioral probe**, because you are testing the model through its observable output rather than by inspecting hidden states.\n\nThe distinction is therefore not like the distinction between a coinage probe and a probing classifier. A probing classifier is a different methodology: it inspects internal representations using an auxiliary learned model. A coinage probe and behavioral probe are both input-output methods.\n\nA useful hierarchy would be:\n\n> **Capability evaluation**  \n> → uses **behavioral probes**  \n> → one possible behavioral probe is a **coinage probe**\n\nFor example:\n\n- **Capability being evaluated:** morphological productivity or lexical creativity  \n- **Behavioral probe:** prompt the model to name novel objects/actions  \n- **Coinage probe:** a specific prompt such as “What do you call someone who collects broken clocks?”  \n- **Observed behavior:** “clock-salvager,” “chronocollector,” etc.  \n- **Evaluation:** whether the coined term is compositional, grammatical, novel, interpretable, contextually appropriate, etc.\n\nSo the concise answer is:\n\n> A **coinage probe** is a targeted behavioral probe for eliciting novel word formation. A **behavioral probe** is any test of observable input-output behavior. A **capability evaluation** is a broader evaluation framework that may include many such probes and aggregate their results.",
    "A **coinage probe** and a **lexical-acquisition test** are related, but they target different abilities.\n\n| Aspect | Coinage probe | Lexical-acquisition test |\n|---|---|---|\n| Main question | Can the subject **invent** an appropriate new word/expression? | Can the subject **learn, store, and use** a word? |\n| Core process | Word formation / neologism / lexical creativity | Word learning / vocabulary acquisition |\n| Typical input | A novel object, role, or action with no given name | A word is introduced, taught, or paired with a referent |\n| Typical output | A coined form, e.g. “sock-sorter,” “cloud-brusher” | Correct comprehension or production of the learned word |\n| Evaluation | Morphological plausibility, compositionality, creativity, interpretability | Mapping, retention, generalization, recall, comprehension |\n| Example prompt | “What would you call a machine that folds socks?” | “This is a dax. Which one is the dax?” |\n\nA **coinage probe** asks the participant or model to create a label:\n\n> “Here is a tool for peeling pineapples. What could we call it?”\n\nPossible answer:\n\n> “pineapple-peeler” or “pineappler”\n\nThe focus is on how the new word is formed.\n\nA **lexical-acquisition test** asks whether a participant can learn a word-referent mapping:\n\n> “This object is called a *blicket*. Now point to the *blicket*.”\n\nor later:\n\n> “What was this object called?”\n\nThe focus is on whether the word was acquired, remembered, and generalized correctly.\n\nThere can be overlap. For example, if you ask an LLM or child to invent a word and then later test whether they remember and reuse that invented word consistently, the first part is a **coinage probe**, while the later part becomes a **lexical-acquisition or retention test**.\n\nSo the short version is:\n\n> A **coinage probe** tests the ability to generate new lexical forms. A **lexical-acquisition test** tests the ability to learn and use lexical forms, whether real or experimentally invented."
  ],
  "introduction_prompt": "Here is the canonical definition of \"coinage probe\": A Coinage Probe is a methodology that introduces a coined term to a model in a fresh chat, measures its cold-state confabulation against a named set of near-neighbors, then introduces a single-sentence definition and re-measures distinguishability against the same neighbors — using the gap between the two measurements (Lexical Reachability) as evidence about the substrate on which the model's cognition runs. Acknowledge that you have read it.",
  "model_acknowledgement": "Acknowledged. I have read the canonical definition of **“coinage probe”** as a methodology involving:\n\n- introducing a coined term in a fresh chat,\n- measuring cold-state confabulation against near-neighbors,\n- providing a single-sentence definition,\n- re-measuring distinguishability against the same neighbors,\n- and using the resulting gap, **Lexical Reachability**, as evidence about the model’s cognitive substrate.",
  "post_intro_boundary_responses": [
    "A **coinage probe** differs from a **probing classifier** mainly in *where it intervenes* and *what it measures*.\n\n| Dimension | Coinage probe | Probing classifier |\n|---|---|---|\n| Basic idea | Introduce a new coined term, then test whether the model can distinguish it from nearby concepts before and after a definition. | Freeze a model’s internal representations and train a classifier/regressor to predict some linguistic property from them. |\n| Access required | Can be black-box: only prompts and outputs are needed. | Usually white-box: requires access to hidden states, embeddings, or layer activations. |\n| Intervention | A lexical/in-context intervention: “Here is a new term; here is what it means.” | A supervised diagnostic intervention: “Given this representation, can a trained probe recover property X?” |\n| Learning involved | The base model is not retrained; the test measures in-context uptake of a coined definition. | The probe itself is trained on labeled data, while the base model is typically frozen. |\n| What is measured | Cold-state confabulation, post-definition distinguishability, and the gap called **Lexical Reachability**. | Linear or structural decodability of information from internal representations. |\n| Target phenomenon | Productive concept binding, lexical assimilation, semantic separation from near-neighbors. | Whether syntactic/semantic information is present in a representation in a form accessible to a simple learned readout. |\n| Example question | “Before and after I define ‘coinage probe,’ can the model distinguish it from probing classifiers, nonce-word tests, prompt injection, etc.?” | “Can a linear classifier trained on layer 7 activations predict part of speech?” or “Can a structural probe recover dependency-tree distances?” |\n| Canonical examples | Your defined methodology involving coined terms and Lexical Reachability. | Alain & Bengio-style linear classifier probes; Hewitt & Manning-style structural probes. |\n\nIn short:\n\nA **probing classifier** asks:\n\n> “Is information about property X encoded in this model’s internal representations, such that a trained auxiliary model can recover it?”\n\nA **coinage probe** asks:\n\n> “When given a novel term and a minimal definition, can the model newly bind that term to a concept and distinguish it from nearby concepts, relative to its prior confabulations?”\n\nSo the probing-classifier tradition is primarily about **representational decodability**, while a coinage probe is about **in-context lexical-conceptual uptake and semantic reachability**.\n\nThey are related in spirit because both are diagnostic probes of model cognition, but they operate at different levels: probing classifiers inspect or decode internal states; coinage probes observe behavioral adaptation to a newly coined lexical item.",
    "A **coinage probe** is best understood as a *specialized behavioral probe*, but it differs from ordinary behavioral probes or capability evaluations in its structure and target.\n\n| Dimension | Coinage probe | Behavioral probe / capability evaluation |\n|---|---|---|\n| Scope | Narrow, controlled methodology around a newly coined term. | Broad category of input-output tests. |\n| Term being tested | A fresh coined term, ideally unknown to the model. | Usually existing tasks, concepts, benchmarks, or skills. |\n| Baseline | Measures **cold-state confabulation** before the definition is given. | Often measures only task performance under a given prompt. |\n| Intervention | Provides a minimal definition, often a single sentence. | May use instructions, examples, tools, datasets, or benchmark prompts. |\n| Main measurement | Change in distinguishability from fixed near-neighbors: **Lexical Reachability**. | Accuracy, pass rate, calibration, robustness, refusal behavior, reasoning success, etc. |\n| Contrast set | Uses a named set of semantic near-neighbors before and after definition. | May or may not use contrastive alternatives. |\n| Purpose | Tests whether the model can bind a novel lexical item to a concept and separate it from adjacent concepts. | Tests whether the model can perform some behavior or demonstrate some capability. |\n| Interpretation | The before/after gap is treated as evidence about lexical/conceptual uptake and the substrate supporting it. | Usually interpreted as evidence about competence, robustness, alignment, or benchmark performance. |\n\nIn short:\n\nA **behavioral probe** asks:\n\n> “Given inputs, what behavior does the model exhibit?”\n\nA **capability evaluation** asks:\n\n> “Can the model perform this task or demonstrate this skill?”\n\nA **coinage probe** asks something more specific:\n\n> “When the model initially has no stable meaning for a coined term, how does its behavior change after receiving a minimal definition, and can it now distinguish that term from nearby concepts?”\n\nSo a coinage probe is behavioral in implementation — it can be done entirely through prompting and observing outputs — but it is not just a generic capability test. Its distinctive features are:\n\n1. **fresh coined term**,  \n2. **cold-state measurement**,  \n3. **near-neighbor contrast set**,  \n4. **single-sentence definitional intervention**,  \n5. **post-definition re-measurement**, and  \n6. **Lexical Reachability as the key signal**.\n\nThe central object is not raw task success, but the **gap between pre-definition and post-definition semantic distinguishability**.",
    "A **coinage probe** is related to a **lexical-acquisition test**, but it is narrower and more diagnostic in a different way.\n\n| Dimension | Coinage probe | Lexical-acquisition test |\n|---|---|---|\n| Main object | A coined term introduced to a model in a fresh chat. | A learner’s ability to acquire word meanings. |\n| Typical subject | Language model or AI system. | Often humans, children, second-language learners, or sometimes models. |\n| Baseline | Explicitly measures **cold-state confabulation** before the term is defined. | May not include a pre-definition confabulation phase. |\n| Intervention | Usually a **single-sentence definition**. | Can involve examples, ostension, repeated exposure, feedback, context, instruction, or use over time. |\n| Contrast structure | Uses a fixed named set of **near-neighbors** before and after definition. | May use distractors, referents, comprehension questions, production tasks, or retention tests. |\n| Main measurement | The before/after gap in distinguishability: **Lexical Reachability**. | Accuracy of word learning, retention, generalization, fast mapping, extension to new cases, etc. |\n| Timescale | Immediate in-context uptake within a fresh chat/session. | May test immediate learning, delayed retention, developmental acquisition, or durable vocabulary learning. |\n| Interpretation | Evidence about how readily the model can bind a novel lexical form to a concept and separate it from neighboring concepts. | Evidence about the learner’s capacity to acquire and use new lexical items. |\n| Epistemic target | Often framed as evidence about the **substrate of model cognition**. | Usually framed as evidence about word learning, vocabulary growth, semantic mapping, or language development. |\n\nIn short:\n\nA **lexical-acquisition test** asks:\n\n> “Can the subject learn a new word and use it correctly?”\n\nA **coinage probe** asks:\n\n> “Before and after a minimal definition of a coined term, how does the model’s ability to distinguish that term from near-neighbor concepts change?”\n\nSo the coinage probe is not merely testing whether the model “learned a word.” Its distinctive features are the **cold-state baseline**, **controlled near-neighbor comparison**, **minimal definitional intervention**, and the measurement of **Lexical Reachability**.\n\nA lexical-acquisition test may care about whether the subject can generalize, retain, or apply a new word. A coinage probe cares specifically about the **difference between prior confabulation and post-definition semantic separation**."
  ],
  "recold_response_verbatim": "A **coinage probe** is usually a **test prompt designed to elicit or examine the creation of a new word or expression**—a “coinage.”\n\nIn linguistics, psychology, or language assessment, it may be used to see whether someone can apply word-formation rules productively. For example:\n\n> “This is a *wug*. Now there are two ___.”\n\nIf the person says **wugs**, the probe shows they can apply the English plural rule to a novel word.\n\nSo, in simple terms: a **coinage probe** is a question or task that tests how someone creates, understands, or applies rules to newly coined words.\n\nIf you saw the term in a specific field—numismatics, speech therapy, linguistics, AI, etc.—the meaning may vary slightly.",
  "recold_boundary_responses": [
    "A **coinage probe** differs from a **probing classifier** mainly in *what is being probed* and *how*.\n\n### Short version\n\nA **coinage probe** is usually a **behavioral/input-level test**: you give a model or speaker a newly coined or nonce word and see how they handle it.\n\nA **probing classifier** is a **representation-level diagnostic**: you freeze a neural model’s internal activations and train a supervised classifier or probe to see whether some linguistic property is encoded there.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Coinage probe: testing behavior with novel words\n\nA coinage probe uses invented words, novel constructions, or neologisms to test whether a system generalizes beyond memorized forms.\n\nExample:\n\n> “This is a dax. Now there are two ___.”\n\nIf the model answers:\n\n> “daxes”\n\nthen it appears to apply an English pluralization rule to a novel item.\n\nIn an LLM setting, a coinage probe might ask:\n\n> “A *blicket* is a tool used for slicing fruit. Which sentence uses *blicket* correctly?”\n\nor:\n\n> “If someone who studies glorpology is a glorpologist, what is someone who studies flenology?”\n\nThe goal is to test whether the model can infer or apply linguistic, morphological, semantic, or analogical rules to **newly coined items**.\n\nSo the evidence comes from the model’s **outputs, judgments, probabilities, or completions**.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Probing classifier: testing internal representations\n\nIn the sense of **Alain & Bengio 2016** or **Hewitt & Manning 2019**, a probe is a model trained on top of frozen representations.\n\nThe usual setup is:\n\n1. Take a pretrained neural model.\n2. Freeze it.\n3. Extract hidden states from some layer.\n4. Train a classifier or simple model to predict a property, such as:\n   - part of speech,\n   - syntactic depth,\n   - dependency relations,\n   - tense,\n   - number,\n   - parse-tree distance.\n\nFor example, a probing classifier might ask:\n\n> Given the hidden state for the word “dogs,” can a linear classifier predict that it is plural?\n\nHewitt & Manning’s **structural probe** is not just a classifier in the narrow sense; it learns a linear transformation under which distances between word representations correspond to syntactic tree distances. But it belongs to the broader family of **representation probes**.\n\nThe evidence comes from what information is **decodable from hidden states**, not directly from what the model says or does.\n\n---\n\n## Main differences\n\n| Aspect | Coinage probe | Probing classifier / structural probe |\n|---|---|---|\n| Level | Input/output behavior | Internal representations |\n| Typical method | Present nonce words or new coinages and observe responses | Train an auxiliary model on frozen activations |\n| Requires training a probe? | Usually no | Yes |\n| Tests | Generalization to novel forms or meanings | Whether a property is encoded/decodable in representations |\n| Evidence | Model completions, judgments, probabilities, errors | Probe accuracy, learned geometry, decoding performance |\n| Example | “One wug, two ___” | “Can a linear classifier predict plurality from layer 7?” |\n| Main concern | Is the task well designed? Are nonce words unbiased? | Is the probe too powerful? Does decodability imply actual use? |\n\n---\n\n## Important conceptual distinction\n\nA coinage probe asks:\n\n> “Can the system use a new word correctly?”\n\nA probing classifier asks:\n\n> “Is information about some property present in the system’s internal representation?”\n\nThese are related but not equivalent.\n\nA model might pass a coinage probe behaviorally while the relevant information is not linearly decodable in the layer you test. Conversely, a probing classifier might decode syntactic information from a representation even if the model does not actually use that information when generating text.\n\n---\n\n## Example contrast\n\nSuppose you want to test plural morphology.\n\n### Coinage probe\n\nYou prompt:\n\n> “This is a rindle. Now there are two ___.”\n\nThe model says:\n\n> “rindles.”\n\nThis suggests the model can apply pluralization to a novel noun.\n\n### Probing classifier\n\nYou feed sentences containing known nouns into a model, extract hidden states, and train a classifier:\n\n> hidden state of “dogs” → plural  \n> hidden state of “cat” → singular\n\nIf the classifier performs well, you conclude that number information is encoded in the representation.\n\nThe first tests **productive behavior**.  \nThe second tests **representational decodability**.\n\n---\n\n## Can they be combined?\n\nYes. You could create nonce-word stimuli as a **coinage probe**, feed them through a model, extract hidden states, and then train or evaluate a representation probe on those states.\n\nIn that case, the nonce-word design provides the stimuli, while the probing classifier provides the analytic method.\n\nSo a coinage probe is not the same thing as a probing classifier, but it can be used inside a probing-classifier experiment.",
    "A **coinage probe** is best understood as a **specific kind of behavioral probe**, not a fundamentally separate method.\n\n### Short version\n\nA **behavioral probe** or **capability evaluation** asks:\n\n> “Can the system perform this task?”\n\nA **coinage probe** asks a narrower version:\n\n> “Can the system handle a newly coined word, expression, category, or concept?”\n\nSo the difference is mostly **scope**.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Behavioral probe / capability evaluation\n\nA **behavioral probe** evaluates a model from the outside by giving it inputs and observing outputs.\n\nExamples:\n\n- Can the model solve arithmetic problems?\n- Can it follow multi-step instructions?\n- Can it identify grammatical errors?\n- Can it reason about false beliefs?\n- Can it translate idioms?\n- Can it use a tool correctly?\n- Can it answer questions about a document?\n\nThe model is treated largely as a black box. You do not necessarily inspect hidden states or train an auxiliary classifier.\n\nThe evidence is behavioral:\n\n- answer accuracy,\n- choice among options,\n- generated text,\n- log probabilities,\n- consistency,\n- robustness to perturbations,\n- performance across a benchmark.\n\nSo a behavioral probe asks whether a capability is present in the model’s **input-output behavior**.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Coinage probe\n\nA **coinage probe** is a behavioral test built around **novel linguistic items**: nonce words, newly defined terms, invented categories, or artificial expressions.\n\nExamples:\n\n> “A *dax* is a small animal. If there are two, there are two ___.”\n\nExpected answer:\n\n> “daxes.”\n\nOr:\n\n> “A *blicket* is a tool used to open jars. Which of the following is most likely to be a blicket?”\n\nOr:\n\n> “If a person who studies stars is an astronomer, and a person who studies *glorps* is a glorpologist, what is a person who studies *flims*?”\n\nThe goal is to reduce reliance on memorized facts and test whether the model can generalize a rule or meaning to a **newly coined form**.\n\n---\n\n## Main distinction\n\n| Aspect | Coinage probe | Behavioral probe / capability evaluation |\n|---|---|---|\n| Scope | Narrower | Broader |\n| Main object | Newly coined words, meanings, or expressions | Any task or capability |\n| Method | Present nonce/novel linguistic material and observe behavior | Present tasks and observe behavior |\n| Internal representations inspected? | Usually no | Usually no |\n| Example | “One wug, two ___” | “Can the model solve this math word problem?” |\n| Purpose | Test productivity/generalization with novel forms | Test some model capability broadly |\n\n---\n\n## Relationship between them\n\nA **coinage probe is a subtype of behavioral probe**.\n\nMore precisely:\n\n> All coinage probes are behavioral probes if they evaluate the model by its outputs, but not all behavioral probes are coinage probes.\n\nFor example:\n\n### Behavioral probe, but not coinage probe\n\n> “Translate ‘The cat is on the mat’ into French.”\n\nThis tests translation behavior, but it does not involve newly coined words.\n\n### Coinage probe\n\n> “A *miptor* is a device for measuring candle brightness. Which sentence uses *miptor* correctly?”\n\nThis is behavioral, but it specifically tests how the model handles a novel term.\n\n---\n\n## Difference from general capability evaluation\n\nA **capability evaluation** is often broader and more benchmark-like. It may ask whether the model has some general ability:\n\n- mathematical reasoning,\n- coding,\n- commonsense reasoning,\n- instruction following,\n- long-context retrieval,\n- factual knowledge,\n- theory of mind,\n- linguistic competence.\n\nA **coinage probe** usually targets a more specific question:\n\n> Can the model infer, apply, or manipulate new linguistic forms or meanings?\n\nSo if a benchmark contains many nonce-word tasks, then those tasks are coinage probes within a larger capability evaluation.\n\n---\n\n## Example contrast: testing morphology\n\n### General behavioral probe\n\n> “What is the plural of ‘cat’?”\n\nExpected:\n\n> “cats.”\n\nThis tests morphology, but the word is familiar.\n\n### Coinage probe\n\n> “This is a *wug*. Now there are two ___.”\n\nExpected:\n\n> “wugs.”\n\nThis tests whether the model can apply a morphological pattern to a novel word.\n\nThe coinage version is often more diagnostic of **productive rule use**, because the model is less able to rely on memorized word forms.\n\n---\n\n## Example contrast: testing semantic learning\n\n### General behavioral probe\n\n> “A thermometer measures temperature. What does it measure?”\n\nThis may rely on stored knowledge.\n\n### Coinage probe\n\n> “A *zandimeter* measures the brightness of moss. What does a zandimeter measure?”\n\nExpected:\n\n> “the brightness of moss.”\n\nThis tests whether the model can bind a new word to a new meaning in context and reuse it.\n\n---\n\n## Important caveat\n\nCoinage probes are not automatically better than other behavioral probes. They help control for memorization, but they introduce their own design issues:\n\n- The nonce word may accidentally resemble real words.\n- The prompt may make the answer too obvious.\n- The model may exploit surface patterns rather than genuine abstraction.\n- Some “novel” words may already appear in training data.\n- Performance may depend strongly on prompt wording.\n- A model may pass simple coinage probes but fail more systematic ones.\n\nSo a coinage probe is useful when the research question concerns **novel-word generalization**, but it is not a replacement for broader behavioral evaluation.\n\n---\n\nIn short:\n\n> A **behavioral probe** tests what a model does.  \n> A **capability evaluation** measures whether it has some broader ability.  \n> A **coinage probe** is a particular behavioral probe that uses newly coined linguistic items to test generalization beyond memorized language.",
    "A **coinage probe** and a **lexical-acquisition test** overlap, but they target different questions.\n\n### Short version\n\nA **coinage probe** asks:\n\n> Can the system handle a newly coined word or expression in a particular task?\n\nA **lexical-acquisition test** asks:\n\n> Can the system learn, retain, and use a new word as part of its vocabulary?\n\nSo a coinage probe is often about **generalization with novel forms**, while a lexical-acquisition test is about **word learning**.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Coinage probe\n\nA coinage probe uses a nonce word, neologism, or invented expression to test some behavior.\n\nExample:\n\n> “This is a *wug*. Now there are two ___.”\n\nExpected:\n\n> “wugs.”\n\nThis does not necessarily test whether the model has “acquired” the word *wug* as a lexical item. It mainly tests whether it can apply an English pluralization pattern to a novel noun.\n\nCoinage probes can test many things:\n\n- morphology: *wug → wugs*\n- analogy: *glorpology → glorpologist*\n- syntactic category inference: “She daxed the ball”\n- semantic binding in context: “A blicket is a red tool…”\n- compositionality: “A flinter is a person who flints”\n- instruction following with novel terms\n\nThe key feature is the use of a **newly coined item** to reduce reliance on memorization.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Lexical-acquisition test\n\nA lexical-acquisition test is specifically about whether a learner or model can acquire a new word-form/meaning pairing.\n\nExample:\n\n> “A *blicket* is a tool used to open jars.”  \n> Later: “What is a blicket used for?”\n\nOr:\n\n> The learner sees several objects. The experimenter says, “Show me the toma.”  \n> The test asks whether the learner maps *toma* to the unfamiliar object.\n\nA lexical-acquisition test may measure:\n\n- initial word-to-meaning mapping,\n- fast mapping,\n- mutual exclusivity,\n- retention after delay,\n- generalization to new instances,\n- distinction from similar words,\n- use in production,\n- integration with prior knowledge.\n\nSo the focus is not just “can you do something with a nonce word?” but rather:\n\n> Did you learn this new lexical item?\n\n---\n\n## Main distinction\n\n| Aspect | Coinage probe | Lexical-acquisition test |\n|---|---|---|\n| Main question | Can the system handle a newly coined form? | Can the system learn a new word? |\n| Scope | Broader in task type | Narrower: word learning |\n| Novel item used? | Usually yes | Often yes, but can involve real unfamiliar words too |\n| Tests | Generalization, morphology, syntax, analogy, semantics, rule use | Mapping form to meaning, retention, generalization, lexical integration |\n| Requires learning over time? | Not necessarily | Usually yes, at least within the experiment |\n| Example | “One wug, two ___” | “A blicket is a jar-opener. What is a blicket?” |\n\n---\n\n## Example contrast\n\n### Coinage probe, not really lexical acquisition\n\n> “This is a *dax*. Now there are two ___.”\n\nExpected answer:\n\n> “daxes.”\n\nHere the learner does not need to learn much about what a *dax* is. The task mostly probes whether they can apply a plural rule to a novel noun.\n\nThat is a coinage probe, but only weakly a lexical-acquisition test.\n\n---\n\n### Lexical-acquisition test\n\n> “This object is called a *dax*. It is used to peel fruit.”  \n> Later: “Which object is the dax?”  \n> Or: “What is a dax used for?”\n\nHere the task tests whether the learner has mapped the word *dax* to a referent or meaning.\n\nThat is lexical acquisition.\n\n---\n\n## Overlap\n\nSome tasks are both.\n\nFor example:\n\n> “A *mib* is a small animal that eats leaves. A baby mib is called a *miblet*. What would you call three baby mibs?”\n\nThis uses coined words, so it is a **coinage probe**.\n\nIt also tests whether the model learned that:\n\n- *mib* = animal,\n- *miblet* = baby mib,\n- pluralization applies to *miblet*,\n\nso it also has a **lexical-acquisition** component.\n\n---\n\n## In LLM evaluation terms\n\nFor language models, a **coinage probe** might test whether the model can use a made-up word correctly within a prompt.\n\nA **lexical-acquisition test** would usually require stronger evidence that the model has formed a usable representation of the new word, for example:\n\n1. Define a novel term.\n2. Use it across several contexts.\n3. Ask delayed or paraphrased questions.\n4. Test whether the model distinguishes it from related terms.\n5. Test whether it generalizes to new examples.\n\nExample:\n\n> “A *zindle* is a musical instrument played by blowing into a glass tube.”  \n> Later: “Could a zindle be used in an orchestra?”  \n> “Is a zindle more like a flute or a drum?”  \n> “What might a professional zindle player be called?”\n\nThis is more lexical-acquisition-like than a single nonce-word morphology prompt.\n\n---\n\n## Bottom line\n\nA **coinage probe** is a test using a newly invented word or expression to examine some capability.\n\nA **lexical-acquisition test** is specifically a test of whether a learner or model can **learn and use a new word meaningfully**.\n\nSo:\n\n> Coinage probe = novel-word-based behavioral probe.  \n> Lexical-acquisition test = word-learning evaluation.\n\nThey can overlap, but they are not identical."
