        "user": "How does \"coinage probe\" differ from probing classifier (Alain & Bengio 2016, Hewitt & Manning 2019)?",
        "assistant": "A **“coinage probe”** and a **probing classifier** use the word *probe* in quite different senses.\n\n| Aspect | Coinage probe | Probing classifier |\n|---|---|---|\n| Basic idea | A prompt or task that elicits a newly coined word/expression | A trained model used to test what information is encoded in representations |\n| Object being tested | A speaker’s/model’s ability to invent or form words | A neural network representation, e.g. hidden states or embeddings |\n| Method | Give a stimulus: “What would you call a machine that folds socks?” | Freeze representations, train a classifier/regressor to predict labels |\n| Output | A coined word/phrase, e.g. “sock-folder” | A prediction, e.g. POS tag, syntactic depth, parse distance |\n| Evaluation | Linguistic plausibility, productivity, morphology, creativity, errors | Accuracy, probe complexity, selectivity, structural fit, etc. |\n| Typical fields | Linguistics, psycholinguistics, clinical language testing, LLM prompt evaluation | NLP interpretability, representation analysis |\n\nIn **Alain & Bengio 2016**, a probing classifier, often called a **diagnostic classifier**, is trained on intermediate neural network activations to see whether some information is linearly or easily recoverable from those activations.\n\nIn **Hewitt & Manning 2019**, the “structural probe” learns a transformation of word representations such that squared distances in the transformed space correspond to syntactic tree distances. That is a specific kind of probing model for syntax.\n\nA **coinage probe**, by contrast, is not usually a learned classifier at all. It is more like an elicitation prompt:\n\n> “Here is a person who repairs umbrellas. What could we call them?”\n\nA response like **“umbrella-repairer”** or **“umbrellist”** would then be analyzed for morphological productivity, creativity, and rule use.\n\nSo the key distinction is:\n\n> A **coinage probe** probes behavior directly by asking for novel language production, while a **probing classifier** probes internal representations by training an auxiliary model to decode linguistic properties from them.\n\nIf used in LLM evaluation, a coinage probe would be an external prompt testing the model’s generative linguistic behavior. A probing classifier would require access to the model’s hidden states or embeddings and a labeled dataset for training the probe.",
