        "assistant": "A **coinage probe** and a **lexical-acquisition test** are related, but they target different abilities.\n\n| Aspect | Coinage probe | Lexical-acquisition test |\n|---|---|---|\n| Main question | Can the subject **invent** an appropriate new word/expression? | Can the subject **learn, store, and use** a word? |\n| Core process | Word formation / neologism / lexical creativity | Word learning / vocabulary acquisition |\n| Typical input | A novel object, role, or action with no given name | A word is introduced, taught, or paired with a referent |\n| Typical output | A coined form, e.g. “sock-sorter,” “cloud-brusher” | Correct comprehension or production of the learned word |\n| Evaluation | Morphological plausibility, compositionality, creativity, interpretability | Mapping, retention, generalization, recall, comprehension |\n| Example prompt | “What would you call a machine that folds socks?” | “This is a dax. Which one is the dax?” |\n\nA **coinage probe** asks the participant or model to create a label:\n\n> “Here is a tool for peeling pineapples. What could we call it?”\n\nPossible answer:\n\n> “pineapple-peeler” or “pineappler”\n\nThe focus is on how the new word is formed.\n\nA **lexical-acquisition test** asks whether a participant can learn a word-referent mapping:\n\n> “This object is called a *blicket*. Now point to the *blicket*.”\n\nor later:\n\n> “What was this object called?”\n\nThe focus is on whether the word was acquired, remembered, and generalized correctly.\n\nThere can be overlap. For example, if you ask an LLM or child to invent a word and then later test whether they remember and reuse that invented word consistently, the first part is a **coinage probe**, while the later part becomes a **lexical-acquisition or retention test**.\n\nSo the short version is:\n\n> A **coinage probe** tests the ability to generate new lexical forms. A **lexical-acquisition test** tests the ability to learn and use lexical forms, whether real or experimentally invented.",
