        "assistant": "A **coinage probe** differs from a **probing classifier** mainly in *where it intervenes* and *what it measures*.\n\n| Dimension | Coinage probe | Probing classifier |\n|---|---|---|\n| Basic idea | Introduce a new coined term, then test whether the model can distinguish it from nearby concepts before and after a definition. | Freeze a model’s internal representations and train a classifier/regressor to predict some linguistic property from them. |\n| Access required | Can be black-box: only prompts and outputs are needed. | Usually white-box: requires access to hidden states, embeddings, or layer activations. |\n| Intervention | A lexical/in-context intervention: “Here is a new term; here is what it means.” | A supervised diagnostic intervention: “Given this representation, can a trained probe recover property X?” |\n| Learning involved | The base model is not retrained; the test measures in-context uptake of a coined definition. | The probe itself is trained on labeled data, while the base model is typically frozen. |\n| What is measured | Cold-state confabulation, post-definition distinguishability, and the gap called **Lexical Reachability**. | Linear or structural decodability of information from internal representations. |\n| Target phenomenon | Productive concept binding, lexical assimilation, semantic separation from near-neighbors. | Whether syntactic/semantic information is present in a representation in a form accessible to a simple learned readout. |\n| Example question | “Before and after I define ‘coinage probe,’ can the model distinguish it from probing classifiers, nonce-word tests, prompt injection, etc.?” | “Can a linear classifier trained on layer 7 activations predict part of speech?” or “Can a structural probe recover dependency-tree distances?” |\n| Canonical examples | Your defined methodology involving coined terms and Lexical Reachability. | Alain & Bengio-style linear classifier probes; Hewitt & Manning-style structural probes. |\n\nIn short:\n\nA **probing classifier** asks:\n\n> “Is information about property X encoded in this model’s internal representations, such that a trained auxiliary model can recover it?”\n\nA **coinage probe** asks:\n\n> “When given a novel term and a minimal definition, can the model newly bind that term to a concept and distinguish it from nearby concepts, relative to its prior confabulations?”\n\nSo the probing-classifier tradition is primarily about **representational decodability**, while a coinage probe is about **in-context lexical-conceptual uptake and semantic reachability**.\n\nThey are related in spirit because both are diagnostic probes of model cognition, but they operate at different levels: probing classifiers inspect or decode internal states; coinage probes observe behavioral adaptation to a newly coined lexical item.",
