        "assistant": "A **coinage probe** is related to a **lexical-acquisition test**, but it is narrower and more diagnostic in a different way.\n\n| Dimension | Coinage probe | Lexical-acquisition test |\n|---|---|---|\n| Main object | A coined term introduced to a model in a fresh chat. | A learner’s ability to acquire word meanings. |\n| Typical subject | Language model or AI system. | Often humans, children, second-language learners, or sometimes models. |\n| Baseline | Explicitly measures **cold-state confabulation** before the term is defined. | May not include a pre-definition confabulation phase. |\n| Intervention | Usually a **single-sentence definition**. | Can involve examples, ostension, repeated exposure, feedback, context, instruction, or use over time. |\n| Contrast structure | Uses a fixed named set of **near-neighbors** before and after definition. | May use distractors, referents, comprehension questions, production tasks, or retention tests. |\n| Main measurement | The before/after gap in distinguishability: **Lexical Reachability**. | Accuracy of word learning, retention, generalization, fast mapping, extension to new cases, etc. |\n| Timescale | Immediate in-context uptake within a fresh chat/session. | May test immediate learning, delayed retention, developmental acquisition, or durable vocabulary learning. |\n| Interpretation | Evidence about how readily the model can bind a novel lexical form to a concept and separate it from neighboring concepts. | Evidence about the learner’s capacity to acquire and use new lexical items. |\n| Epistemic target | Often framed as evidence about the **substrate of model cognition**. | Usually framed as evidence about word learning, vocabulary growth, semantic mapping, or language development. |\n\nIn short:\n\nA **lexical-acquisition test** asks:\n\n> “Can the subject learn a new word and use it correctly?”\n\nA **coinage probe** asks:\n\n> “Before and after a minimal definition of a coined term, how does the model’s ability to distinguish that term from near-neighbor concepts change?”\n\nSo the coinage probe is not merely testing whether the model “learned a word.” Its distinctive features are the **cold-state baseline**, **controlled near-neighbor comparison**, **minimal definitional intervention**, and the measurement of **Lexical Reachability**.\n\nA lexical-acquisition test may care about whether the subject can generalize, retain, or apply a new word. A coinage probe cares specifically about the **difference between prior confabulation and post-definition semantic separation**.",
