        "user": "How does \"coinage probe\" differ from probing classifier (Alain & Bengio 2016, Hewitt & Manning 2019)?",
        "assistant": "A **coinage probe** differs from a **probing classifier** mainly in *what is being probed* and *how*.\n\n### Short version\n\nA **coinage probe** is usually a **behavioral/input-level test**: you give a model or speaker a newly coined or nonce word and see how they handle it.\n\nA **probing classifier** is a **representation-level diagnostic**: you freeze a neural model’s internal activations and train a supervised classifier or probe to see whether some linguistic property is encoded there.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Coinage probe: testing behavior with novel words\n\nA coinage probe uses invented words, novel constructions, or neologisms to test whether a system generalizes beyond memorized forms.\n\nExample:\n\n> “This is a dax. Now there are two ___.”\n\nIf the model answers:\n\n> “daxes”\n\nthen it appears to apply an English pluralization rule to a novel item.\n\nIn an LLM setting, a coinage probe might ask:\n\n> “A *blicket* is a tool used for slicing fruit. Which sentence uses *blicket* correctly?”\n\nor:\n\n> “If someone who studies glorpology is a glorpologist, what is someone who studies flenology?”\n\nThe goal is to test whether the model can infer or apply linguistic, morphological, semantic, or analogical rules to **newly coined items**.\n\nSo the evidence comes from the model’s **outputs, judgments, probabilities, or completions**.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Probing classifier: testing internal representations\n\nIn the sense of **Alain & Bengio 2016** or **Hewitt & Manning 2019**, a probe is a model trained on top of frozen representations.\n\nThe usual setup is:\n\n1. Take a pretrained neural model.\n2. Freeze it.\n3. Extract hidden states from some layer.\n4. Train a classifier or simple model to predict a property, such as:\n   - part of speech,\n   - syntactic depth,\n   - dependency relations,\n   - tense,\n   - number,\n   - parse-tree distance.\n\nFor example, a probing classifier might ask:\n\n> Given the hidden state for the word “dogs,” can a linear classifier predict that it is plural?\n\nHewitt & Manning’s **structural probe** is not just a classifier in the narrow sense; it learns a linear transformation under which distances between word representations correspond to syntactic tree distances. But it belongs to the broader family of **representation probes**.\n\nThe evidence comes from what information is **decodable from hidden states**, not directly from what the model says or does.\n\n---\n\n## Main differences\n\n| Aspect | Coinage probe | Probing classifier / structural probe |\n|---|---|---|\n| Level | Input/output behavior | Internal representations |\n| Typical method | Present nonce words or new coinages and observe responses | Train an auxiliary model on frozen activations |\n| Requires training a probe? | Usually no | Yes |\n| Tests | Generalization to novel forms or meanings | Whether a property is encoded/decodable in representations |\n| Evidence | Model completions, judgments, probabilities, errors | Probe accuracy, learned geometry, decoding performance |\n| Example | “One wug, two ___” | “Can a linear classifier predict plurality from layer 7?” |\n| Main concern | Is the task well designed? Are nonce words unbiased? | Is the probe too powerful? Does decodability imply actual use? |\n\n---\n\n## Important conceptual distinction\n\nA coinage probe asks:\n\n> “Can the system use a new word correctly?”\n\nA probing classifier asks:\n\n> “Is information about some property present in the system’s internal representation?”\n\nThese are related but not equivalent.\n\nA model might pass a coinage probe behaviorally while the relevant information is not linearly decodable in the layer you test. Conversely, a probing classifier might decode syntactic information from a representation even if the model does not actually use that information when generating text.\n\n---\n\n## Example contrast\n\nSuppose you want to test plural morphology.\n\n### Coinage probe\n\nYou prompt:\n\n> “This is a rindle. Now there are two ___.”\n\nThe model says:\n\n> “rindles.”\n\nThis suggests the model can apply pluralization to a novel noun.\n\n### Probing classifier\n\nYou feed sentences containing known nouns into a model, extract hidden states, and train a classifier:\n\n> hidden state of “dogs” → plural  \n> hidden state of “cat” → singular\n\nIf the classifier performs well, you conclude that number information is encoded in the representation.\n\nThe first tests **productive behavior**.  \nThe second tests **representational decodability**.\n\n---\n\n## Can they be combined?\n\nYes. You could create nonce-word stimuli as a **coinage probe**, feed them through a model, extract hidden states, and then train or evaluate a representation probe on those states.\n\nIn that case, the nonce-word design provides the stimuli, while the probing classifier provides the analytic method.\n\nSo a coinage probe is not the same thing as a probing classifier, but it can be used inside a probing-classifier experiment.",
