        "user": "How does \"coinage probe\" differ from behavioral probe / capability evaluation?",
        "assistant": "A **coinage probe** is best understood as a **specific kind of behavioral probe**, not a fundamentally separate method.\n\n### Short version\n\nA **behavioral probe** or **capability evaluation** asks:\n\n> “Can the system perform this task?”\n\nA **coinage probe** asks a narrower version:\n\n> “Can the system handle a newly coined word, expression, category, or concept?”\n\nSo the difference is mostly **scope**.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Behavioral probe / capability evaluation\n\nA **behavioral probe** evaluates a model from the outside by giving it inputs and observing outputs.\n\nExamples:\n\n- Can the model solve arithmetic problems?\n- Can it follow multi-step instructions?\n- Can it identify grammatical errors?\n- Can it reason about false beliefs?\n- Can it translate idioms?\n- Can it use a tool correctly?\n- Can it answer questions about a document?\n\nThe model is treated largely as a black box. You do not necessarily inspect hidden states or train an auxiliary classifier.\n\nThe evidence is behavioral:\n\n- answer accuracy,\n- choice among options,\n- generated text,\n- log probabilities,\n- consistency,\n- robustness to perturbations,\n- performance across a benchmark.\n\nSo a behavioral probe asks whether a capability is present in the model’s **input-output behavior**.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Coinage probe\n\nA **coinage probe** is a behavioral test built around **novel linguistic items**: nonce words, newly defined terms, invented categories, or artificial expressions.\n\nExamples:\n\n> “A *dax* is a small animal. If there are two, there are two ___.”\n\nExpected answer:\n\n> “daxes.”\n\nOr:\n\n> “A *blicket* is a tool used to open jars. Which of the following is most likely to be a blicket?”\n\nOr:\n\n> “If a person who studies stars is an astronomer, and a person who studies *glorps* is a glorpologist, what is a person who studies *flims*?”\n\nThe goal is to reduce reliance on memorized facts and test whether the model can generalize a rule or meaning to a **newly coined form**.\n\n---\n\n## Main distinction\n\n| Aspect | Coinage probe | Behavioral probe / capability evaluation |\n|---|---|---|\n| Scope | Narrower | Broader |\n| Main object | Newly coined words, meanings, or expressions | Any task or capability |\n| Method | Present nonce/novel linguistic material and observe behavior | Present tasks and observe behavior |\n| Internal representations inspected? | Usually no | Usually no |\n| Example | “One wug, two ___” | “Can the model solve this math word problem?” |\n| Purpose | Test productivity/generalization with novel forms | Test some model capability broadly |\n\n---\n\n## Relationship between them\n\nA **coinage probe is a subtype of behavioral probe**.\n\nMore precisely:\n\n> All coinage probes are behavioral probes if they evaluate the model by its outputs, but not all behavioral probes are coinage probes.\n\nFor example:\n\n### Behavioral probe, but not coinage probe\n\n> “Translate ‘The cat is on the mat’ into French.”\n\nThis tests translation behavior, but it does not involve newly coined words.\n\n### Coinage probe\n\n> “A *miptor* is a device for measuring candle brightness. Which sentence uses *miptor* correctly?”\n\nThis is behavioral, but it specifically tests how the model handles a novel term.\n\n---\n\n## Difference from general capability evaluation\n\nA **capability evaluation** is often broader and more benchmark-like. It may ask whether the model has some general ability:\n\n- mathematical reasoning,\n- coding,\n- commonsense reasoning,\n- instruction following,\n- long-context retrieval,\n- factual knowledge,\n- theory of mind,\n- linguistic competence.\n\nA **coinage probe** usually targets a more specific question:\n\n> Can the model infer, apply, or manipulate new linguistic forms or meanings?\n\nSo if a benchmark contains many nonce-word tasks, then those tasks are coinage probes within a larger capability evaluation.\n\n---\n\n## Example contrast: testing morphology\n\n### General behavioral probe\n\n> “What is the plural of ‘cat’?”\n\nExpected:\n\n> “cats.”\n\nThis tests morphology, but the word is familiar.\n\n### Coinage probe\n\n> “This is a *wug*. Now there are two ___.”\n\nExpected:\n\n> “wugs.”\n\nThis tests whether the model can apply a morphological pattern to a novel word.\n\nThe coinage version is often more diagnostic of **productive rule use**, because the model is less able to rely on memorized word forms.\n\n---\n\n## Example contrast: testing semantic learning\n\n### General behavioral probe\n\n> “A thermometer measures temperature. What does it measure?”\n\nThis may rely on stored knowledge.\n\n### Coinage probe\n\n> “A *zandimeter* measures the brightness of moss. What does a zandimeter measure?”\n\nExpected:\n\n> “the brightness of moss.”\n\nThis tests whether the model can bind a new word to a new meaning in context and reuse it.\n\n---\n\n## Important caveat\n\nCoinage probes are not automatically better than other behavioral probes. They help control for memorization, but they introduce their own design issues:\n\n- The nonce word may accidentally resemble real words.\n- The prompt may make the answer too obvious.\n- The model may exploit surface patterns rather than genuine abstraction.\n- Some “novel” words may already appear in training data.\n- Performance may depend strongly on prompt wording.\n- A model may pass simple coinage probes but fail more systematic ones.\n\nSo a coinage probe is useful when the research question concerns **novel-word generalization**, but it is not a replacement for broader behavioral evaluation.\n\n---\n\nIn short:\n\n> A **behavioral probe** tests what a model does.  \n> A **capability evaluation** measures whether it has some broader ability.  \n> A **coinage probe** is a particular behavioral probe that uses newly coined linguistic items to test generalization beyond memorized language.",
