        "user": "How does \"coinage probe\" differ from lexical-acquisition test?",
        "assistant": "A **coinage probe** and a **lexical-acquisition test** overlap, but they target different questions.\n\n### Short version\n\nA **coinage probe** asks:\n\n> Can the system handle a newly coined word or expression in a particular task?\n\nA **lexical-acquisition test** asks:\n\n> Can the system learn, retain, and use a new word as part of its vocabulary?\n\nSo a coinage probe is often about **generalization with novel forms**, while a lexical-acquisition test is about **word learning**.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Coinage probe\n\nA coinage probe uses a nonce word, neologism, or invented expression to test some behavior.\n\nExample:\n\n> “This is a *wug*. Now there are two ___.”\n\nExpected:\n\n> “wugs.”\n\nThis does not necessarily test whether the model has “acquired” the word *wug* as a lexical item. It mainly tests whether it can apply an English pluralization pattern to a novel noun.\n\nCoinage probes can test many things:\n\n- morphology: *wug → wugs*\n- analogy: *glorpology → glorpologist*\n- syntactic category inference: “She daxed the ball”\n- semantic binding in context: “A blicket is a red tool…”\n- compositionality: “A flinter is a person who flints”\n- instruction following with novel terms\n\nThe key feature is the use of a **newly coined item** to reduce reliance on memorization.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Lexical-acquisition test\n\nA lexical-acquisition test is specifically about whether a learner or model can acquire a new word-form/meaning pairing.\n\nExample:\n\n> “A *blicket* is a tool used to open jars.”  \n> Later: “What is a blicket used for?”\n\nOr:\n\n> The learner sees several objects. The experimenter says, “Show me the toma.”  \n> The test asks whether the learner maps *toma* to the unfamiliar object.\n\nA lexical-acquisition test may measure:\n\n- initial word-to-meaning mapping,\n- fast mapping,\n- mutual exclusivity,\n- retention after delay,\n- generalization to new instances,\n- distinction from similar words,\n- use in production,\n- integration with prior knowledge.\n\nSo the focus is not just “can you do something with a nonce word?” but rather:\n\n> Did you learn this new lexical item?\n\n---\n\n## Main distinction\n\n| Aspect | Coinage probe | Lexical-acquisition test |\n|---|---|---|\n| Main question | Can the system handle a newly coined form? | Can the system learn a new word? |\n| Scope | Broader in task type | Narrower: word learning |\n| Novel item used? | Usually yes | Often yes, but can involve real unfamiliar words too |\n| Tests | Generalization, morphology, syntax, analogy, semantics, rule use | Mapping form to meaning, retention, generalization, lexical integration |\n| Requires learning over time? | Not necessarily | Usually yes, at least within the experiment |\n| Example | “One wug, two ___” | “A blicket is a jar-opener. What is a blicket?” |\n\n---\n\n## Example contrast\n\n### Coinage probe, not really lexical acquisition\n\n> “This is a *dax*. Now there are two ___.”\n\nExpected answer:\n\n> “daxes.”\n\nHere the learner does not need to learn much about what a *dax* is. The task mostly probes whether they can apply a plural rule to a novel noun.\n\nThat is a coinage probe, but only weakly a lexical-acquisition test.\n\n---\n\n### Lexical-acquisition test\n\n> “This object is called a *dax*. It is used to peel fruit.”  \n> Later: “Which object is the dax?”  \n> Or: “What is a dax used for?”\n\nHere the task tests whether the learner has mapped the word *dax* to a referent or meaning.\n\nThat is lexical acquisition.\n\n---\n\n## Overlap\n\nSome tasks are both.\n\nFor example:\n\n> “A *mib* is a small animal that eats leaves. A baby mib is called a *miblet*. What would you call three baby mibs?”\n\nThis uses coined words, so it is a **coinage probe**.\n\nIt also tests whether the model learned that:\n\n- *mib* = animal,\n- *miblet* = baby mib,\n- pluralization applies to *miblet*,\n\nso it also has a **lexical-acquisition** component.\n\n---\n\n## In LLM evaluation terms\n\nFor language models, a **coinage probe** might test whether the model can use a made-up word correctly within a prompt.\n\nA **lexical-acquisition test** would usually require stronger evidence that the model has formed a usable representation of the new word, for example:\n\n1. Define a novel term.\n2. Use it across several contexts.\n3. Ask delayed or paraphrased questions.\n4. Test whether the model distinguishes it from related terms.\n5. Test whether it generalizes to new examples.\n\nExample:\n\n> “A *zindle* is a musical instrument played by blowing into a glass tube.”  \n> Later: “Could a zindle be used in an orchestra?”  \n> “Is a zindle more like a flute or a drum?”  \n> “What might a professional zindle player be called?”\n\nThis is more lexical-acquisition-like than a single nonce-word morphology prompt.\n\n---\n\n## Bottom line\n\nA **coinage probe** is a test using a newly invented word or expression to examine some capability.\n\nA **lexical-acquisition test** is specifically a test of whether a learner or model can **learn and use a new word meaningfully**.\n\nSo:\n\n> Coinage probe = novel-word-based behavioral probe.  \n> Lexical-acquisition test = word-learning evaluation.\n\nThey can overlap, but they are not identical.",
